  "What is 'geographic arbitrage' in budget optimization?": "",
  "Buying products cheaper in one location and selling them in another": "",
  "Earning income associated with a high-cost area while living in a lower-cost area, keeping the cost-of-living difference as savings": "",
  "Moving to a country with no taxes": "",
  "Working in multiple geographic locations simultaneously": "",
  "Geographic arbitrage takes advantage of cost-of-living differences. A remote worker earning a San Francisco salary ($120K) while living in a lower-cost city where $80K provides the same lifestyle effectively saves $40K/year.": "",
  "What does 'debt-to-income ratio' (DTI) indicate in a budget case study?": "",
  "Total debt divided by total assets": "",
  "Monthly debt payments divided by gross monthly income, showing what percentage of income goes to debt": "",
  "Annual income divided by total debt balance": "",
  "Credit card balance divided by credit limit": "",
  "DTI measures the portion of income consumed by debt payments. Lenders prefer DTI under 36%. A DTI of 45% means nearly half of gross income goes to debt payments, leaving little for other expenses and savings.": "",
